Arrive at the location at 5:02am yesterday. I drove out of the way to go there since they opened at 5am.The lights came on as I pulled up. I walk to the front where somebody else is waiting. There are 2 employees inside the store. Over the next ten minutes another 5-6 customers walk up.  5:15 somebody comes to the door, opens it to grab the papers, doesn't say anything to the nearly 10 people standing there, shuts the door and locks it.  5:30 the (what appears to be) manager arrives. Walks to the door, unlocks it, goes in and immediately locks it. Doesn't say a word.  So finally at 5:50 as I'm already past the point of being late to work, I knock on the door, all 3 employees look at me and just go back to what they were doing and ignore me. So then I continue knocking until I eventually get somebody to come to the door. She answers the door and frustratingly says "can I help you?". I ask if they're going to be opening soon, we've all been waiting. She says "we're opening late today". So I ask "so 6:00-6:10?". She says "after 6" and then shuts the door and walks away. So then everyone walks away completely frustrated by the complete disregard.  The stores hours clearly state they open at 5:00am. If you're going to open late, inform the numerous customers that have been waiting.  I can only hope the store stops getting business. I've certainly never been treated so poorly by a food industry business before.

Great coffee and fresh pumpkin bread. But to this New Yorker's eyes, everything in DC looks closed, wot with the propensity for smoked glass. Outside, a trio of seats  under the one remaining tree promise some relief, but their grey metal construction is uncomfortable enough to leave you wishing your coffee break was over.

This is by far one of the best coffeehouse experiences I've ever had in DC.  Julie was completely awesome!  I explained to her that I love tea, but unfortunately that I can only drink decafinated.  She suggested some cool flavors and some of which could mix well together.  I saw her offering the same help for other customers, and I could tell that she really got into her job.  As you can imagine how crazy this place gets in the mornings, I was really impressed.  I will definitely have to take this detour again!

I went to this Starbucks many times because it's the closest to where I work but most of my experiences haven't been great. I work the midnight shift and wait all night for them to open at 5 am. More than once at 5am they're not open. 5:05 am they're not open. 5:08, not open again. On Thursday, 5/22, I waited until 5:10 am.  An employee walked right past me and the other people standing at the door to put milk on the condiment counter, looked at us and still did not open the door. It's not like they didn't know we were standing there. I decided that moment that that location had lost my business. Another man said the same thing. When they did open, you better hope there was someone there that knew how to make a frappuccino, or an espresso drink because not all employees were trained. More than once I had to wait for someone to come from the back to make my drink. I now drive to the one in the SE which is always open on time or the one in the SW. I get Starbucks everyday, but I won't be making my runs to this location any more.
